div#intro.section
    h1 üìà Datashaper

    p This tool reformats a CSV dataset so it will display well in <a href="https://www.theatlas.com/">Atlas</a>. If you are familiar with "pivot tables" in Excel or Google Spreadsheets, this works in a similar way.

div#upload.section
    h2 Upload a CSV file

    p Select a <code>.csv</code> file to upload. Your data must have a header row!
    
    p If you have an Excel file (<code>.xls</code> or <code>.xlsx</code>) you will first need to "Save As" and select "CSV" as the file type.
    
    input(type="file")
    
    p Or, paste CSV here:
    
    textarea
    
    a.sample(href="#") Load sample state taxes dataset

div#columns.section
    h2 Choose your columns
    
    p Your original table has <span class="column-count"></span> columns and <span class="row-count"></span> rows.

    p Please select how each column from the original table should be displayed in the new table. You will see a preview of the new table to the right. üëâüèΩ
    
    ul
        li <strong class="rows">Rows</strong> are the first column of the new table. These are used as the "labels" in Atlas. (Country names, for example.)
        li <strong class="columns">Columns</strong> appear across the top of the table. One new column will be created for each unique value in the original column. Use this option when you want to display multiple data series on one Atlas chart.
        li <strong class="values">Values</strong> are the numeric values that will be charted.
    
    table
        thead
            tr
                th Original column
                th Use as Rows
                th Use as Columns
                th Use as Values
                th Ignore
        tbody
            form
            
    div.warnings

div#aggregation.section
    h2 Decide how to aggregate values
    
    p.reason
    
    p If you aren't sure what to pick, you probably want to choose <strong>add values</strong>.
    
    label Choose a method:
        select
            option(value="sum", selected="selected") Add values
            option(value="average") Average values
            option(value="count") Count number of values
            option(value="countUnique") Count number of unique values
            option(value="min") Use smallest value
            option(value="max") Use largest value
            option(value="first") Use first value from the original data
            option(value="last") Use last value from the original data
            option(value="pct_sum_row") Add values and divide by row total (Percent of row total)
            option(value="pct_sum_col") Add values and divide by column total (Percent of column total)
            option(value="pct_sum_total") Add values and divide by table total (Percent of table total)
            option(value="pct_count_row") Count values and divide by row total (Percent of row count)
            option(value="pct_count_col") Count values and divide by column total (Percent of column count)
            option(value="pct_count_total") Count values and divide by table total (Percent of table count)
            
            
div#options.section
    h2 Tweak as needed
    
    p Use these options to further customize your table.
    
    div.option
        label Sort table
            select#sort
                option(value="rowAsc", selected="selected") Ascending by rows
                option(value="rowDesc") Descending by rows
                option(value="valueAsc") Ascending by value
                option(value="valueDesc") Descending by value
                option(value="none") In the same order as the original data

    div.option
        label Divide values by
            select#divide
                option(value="1") Nothing
                option(value="1000") 1,000
                option(value="1000000") 1,000,000
                option(value="1000000000") 1,000,000,000
                option(value="1000000000000") 1,000,000,000,000

    div.option
        label Digits to include after a decimal point
            select#decimal
                option(value="0") 0
                option(value="1") 1
                option(value="2", selected="selected") 2
                option(value="3") 3
                
    p You're done! Use the pink "Copy table for Atlas" button to copy the table to your clipboard. You can then paste it directly into Atlas.
        
